
@startuml

class Patient {
  - name: String
  - id: String
  - consentGiven: boolean
  - treatments: List<Treatment>
}

class Doctor {
  - name: String
  - id: String
  - diagnoses: List<Diagnosis>
}

class HeadDoctor {
  - name: String
  - id: String
  + approveDiagnosis(diagnosis: Diagnosis): boolean
}

class Illness {
  - name: String
  - priority: Priority
  - treatments: List<Treatment>
}

class Diagnosis {
  - patient: Patient
  - doctor: Doctor
  - illness: Illness
  - date: Date
}

class Treatment {
  - name: String
  - stage: Stage
  - illness: Illness
  - patient: Patient
  - requiresConsent: boolean
  - isApprovedByHeadDoctor: boolean
}

enum Priority {
  HIGH, LOW
}

enum Stage {
  STAGE_1, STAGE_2, STAGE_3
}

Patient "0..*" -- "1" Doctor : assigned to
Doctor "1" --> Diagnosis : makes
HeadDoctor "1" --> Diagnosis : approves
Illness "1" -- "0..*" Treatment : has
Illness "1" -- "0..*" Diagnosis : has
Treatment "1" -- "1" Patient : applied to
Treatment "1" -- "1" Illness : treats

@enduml

---

### Explanation of Key Relationships:

- **Patient** can be assigned to **one or more Doctors**.
- A **Doctor** can make multiple **Diagnoses**.
- The **HeadDoctor** must **approve** each **Diagnosis** before any treatment can proceed.
- An **Illness** may have multiple **Treatments** and may be diagnosed by multiple **Patients**.
- A **Treatment** is associated with a specific **Illness** and **Patient**, and has a current **Stage**.
- Each **Treatment** can be in one of three **Stages**: `STAGE_1`, `STAGE_2`, or `STAGE_3`.
- The **Priority** of an **Illness** (either `HIGH` or `LOW`) affects how treatments are escalated.
- Patients can give **consent** to move their treatments to higher stages.

